[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Institute of Chartered Accountants in Ireland – Written evidence[bold]&#xa0;[bold]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Our Committee, on behalf of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in Ireland, confined its 
[normal]examination
[normal] of the provisions of this Bill to Schedule 5, Insolvency and Company Law.  Our 
[normal]specific
[normal] comments on those provisions are attached herewith.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We respond to a number of the general questions posed in the Call for Written Evidence as 
[normal]follows
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q. 3[bold]              [bold]Are the changes proposed in the draft Bill evidence-based and have any risks associated with the changes been taken adequately into account?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A. 3[bold]              
[normal]We are not convinced of the benefits/risk balance in the proposal to remove the obligation on a bankrupt to present a statement of affairs when the petition is presented by a creditor.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q. 4[bold]              
[normal]Does the draft Bill achieve its purpose of reducing the regulatory burden on business, organisations and individuals effectively and fairly?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A. 4[bold]              
[normal]On balance
[normal], yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q. 5[bold]              
[normal]Will the draft Bill generally benefit businesses by offsetting other regulatory burdens?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A. 5[bold]              
[normal]Reduction in administrative burdens in insolvency assignments will reduce costs. Consequently, more funds will be available for the creditors of the insolvent business.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q. 6[bold]    To what extent does the draft Bill benefit consumers as well as businesses?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A. 6 [bold]   Amendments within Schedule 5 may benefit consumers who are creditors of insolvent
[normal]           
[normal]businesses
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]John Bowen-Walsh
[normal]Secretary
